<h1 style=3D"text-align: left;"><strong>Understanding Gram to Carat Convers=
ion in Jewelry</strong></h1>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">When shopping for or valuing jewelry, one of=
 the most critical aspects is understanding weight measurements. While <str=
ong>grams (g)</strong> are commonly used for measuring gold and precious me=
tals, <strong>carats (ct)</strong> are the standard measurement for diamond=
s and gemstones. Knowing how to convert between these two units is essentia=
l for both buyers and sellers to ensure accurate pricing and evaluation.</p=
>
<h2 style=3D"text-align: left;"><strong>What is a Carat?</strong></h2>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">A <strong>carat (ct)</strong> is a unit of w=
eight used specifically for gemstones and pearls. It should not be confused=
 with "karat," which refers to the purity of gold. The <strong>carat system=
</strong> is used worldwide to provide a standard way of measuring precious=
 stones.</p>
<h3 style=3D"text-align: left;"><strong>Conversion Formula:</strong></h3>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">1 carat (ct) =3D <strong>0.2 grams (g)</stro=
ng><br>1 gram (g) =3D <strong>5 carats (ct)</strong></p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;">This means that if you have a gemstone weigh=
ing 2 grams, you can calculate its weight in carats as follows:</p>
<p style=3D"text-align: left;"><span class=3D"katex-display"><span class=3D=
